	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><span style="font-size: 150%; line-height: normal">OKAY.</span>
<br />
<br />I went back and reread most of this thread, looking for clues. RT9342 was right, there must be some interference coming from the lines near the one between Q1 and pin 21. I even had taken out Q1 and all the nearby resistors, with the wire soldered directly onto pin 21, and still lines. I took the plunge and lifted pin 21, and now my picture is crystal clear.
<br />
<br />Dunno what the screen going black was all about, it's not doing it anymore =)
<br />
<br />Anyway, pretty excited to have the best NES possible. Thanks a ton, you guys =D
<br />
<br />Someone oughtta link this around a bit <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" />
<br />
<br />Edit: Just a small tip if anyone needs it, I took some of the ethernet wire that was leftover, wrapped it around the pin (after desoldering it, of course), and gently tugged at it with some pliers. Possibly not the best way to do it, but it got the job done.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


